the various drivers of diverse gentrification processes in Beirut, Lebanon -- tGentrification in Nigeria: the case of two housing estates in Lagos -- tGentrification in China? -- tEmerging retail gentrification in Santiago de Chile: the case of Italia-Caupolicán -- tGentrification dispositifs in the historic centre of Madrid: a reconsideration of urban governmentality and state-led urban reconfiguration -- tWhen authoritarianism embraces gentrification – the case of Old Damascus, Syria -- tThe place of gentrification in Cape Town -- tConclusion: global gentrifications -- tThe adventure of generic gentrification -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnder contemporary capitalism the extraction of value from the built environment has escalated, working in tandem with other urban processes to lay the foundations for the exploitative processes of gentrification world-wide. Global gentrifications: Uneven development and displacement critically assesses and tests the meaning and significance of gentrification in places outside the ‘usual suspects’ of the Global North. Informed by a rich array of case studies from cities in Asia, Latin America, Africa, Southern Europe, and beyond, the book (re)discovers the important generalities and geographical specificities associated with the uneven process of gentrification globally. It highlights intensifying global struggles over urban space and underlines gentrification as a growing and important battleground in the contemporary world. The book will be of value to students and academics, policy makers, planners and community organisations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGentrification. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Regional Planning.2bisacsh1 aAlexandri, Georgia, econtributor.4ctb4